-- Areva, Bharti, Power Grid, Reliance Power, Marico: India Equity Preview
-- Anoop Agrawal
-- 2010-07-05T01:32:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-05/areva-bharti-power-grid-reliance-power-marico-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or  Sensex , fell
48.38, or 0.3 percent, to 17,460.95. The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on
the National Stock Exchange lost 0.3 percent to 5,237.10. The
 BSE 200 Index  retreated 0.3 percent to 2,223.59.  
 Areva T&D India Ltd.  (ATD IN): The company’s parent, Areva
SA, the world’s biggest maker of nuclear reactors, is in the
final stage of talks with India over “huge” contracts covering
EPR nuclear reactors and fuel, Chief Executive Officer  Anne Lauvergeon  said. Areva T&D India fell 0.1 percent to 289.15
rupees.  
 Bharti Airtel Ltd.  (BHARTI IN): The mobile-phone company
that last month completed a $9 billion acquisition of Zain’s
African assets plans to invest $100 million in Niger over the
next three years, said  Manoj Kohli , chief executive officer of
Bharti’s African unit. Bharti fell 0.1 percent to 264.7 rupees.  
 Ceat India Ltd. (CEAT IN): The company plans to spend 6.3
billion rupees to double capacity at its radial tire unit, the
Business Standard newspaper reported July 3, citing an official
it didn’t name. The shares fell 0.6 percent to 133 rupees.  
 Marico Ltd.  (MRCO IN): The maker of hair-grooming products
is reorganizing its Kaya Skin Clinic outlets in India to cut
losses and doesn’t expect the unit to break even until the year
starting April 1, the Press Trust of India reported on July 4,
citing Chief of Human Resources and Strategy,  Milind Sarwate .
The shares fell 3.4 percent to 126.5 rupees.  
 Power Grid Corp. of India Ltd.  (PWGR IN): The nation’s
biggest electricity transmission company approved selling a 20
percent stake, including a fresh issue of shares worth 10
percent and divestment of an equal amount of government holdings,
according to a statement on the Bombay Stock Exchange. The stock
rose 0.3 percent to 103.55 rupees.  
 Reliance Power Ltd.  (RPWR IN) and  Reliance Natural
Resources Ltd. , both owned by billionaire  Anil Ambani , agreed to
merge through the exchange of one Reliance Power share for every
four Natural Resources shares, according to an e-mailed
statement from the parent company. Reliance Power rose 3.4
percent to 175.3 rupees, while Reliance Natural Resources (RNR
IN) fell 1.5 percent to 63.95 rupees.  
 Shoppers Stop Ltd.  (SHOP IN): The retail chain plans to
double sales to 30 billion rupees in five years, the Press Trust
of India reported yesterday, citing Chief Executive Officer
 Govind Shrikhande . The shares fell 1.3 percent to 549.05 rupees.  
